\title{Helek Entropy Stream: HD-72 Session 5 → Rauzy Tiling}
\taxon{experiment}
\author{monaduck1069}
\import{macros}
\date{2026-04-11}
\tag{eeg}
\tag{entropy}
\tag{tiling}
\tag{aptos}
\tag{randomness}
\meta{modality}{electrophysiological}
\meta{device}{Cognionics HD-72 64CH}
\meta{session}{5}
\meta{heleks}{250}

\p{Pipeline from 4-channel EEG recording to on-chain entropy commitment via Rauzy tiling. Session 5 (14 min, 2026-04-06) is the only recording with connected electrodes — AFF3 (120 kΩ), FFC3h (87 kΩ), FFC4 (163 kΩ), FCC3 (100 kΩ). All left frontocentral cortex.}

\subtree{\title{Pipeline}
\taxon{definition}

\pre{\startverb
HD-72 dry EEG (4 connected channels, 500 Hz)
  → bandpass 1-45 Hz (scipy butter order 4)
    → helek windows (3.334s = 1667 samples)
      → Welch PSD per channel per helek
        → 5-band power (δ θ α β γ)
          → Shannon entropy (bits)
          → GF(3) trit (α-dominant=-1, β-dominant=+1, else=0)
            → SHA-256 of spectral summary → commit_hash
            → SHA-256 first 8 bytes → splitmix_seed (uint64)
              → SplitMix64 → brain_color (hex RGB)
              → Rauzy substitution index → tile type (a/b/c)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{\title{Results: 250 Heleks}
\taxon{finding}

\table{
\tr{\th{Metric}\th{Value}}
\tr{\td{Duration}\td{837s (13.9 min)}}
\tr{\td{Heleks}\td{250}}
\tr{\td{Entropy range}\td{0.083 — 2.318 bits}}
\tr{\td{Mean entropy}\td{0.795 bits}}
\tr{\td{Trit distribution}\td{-1: 5, 0: 243, +1: 2}}
\tr{\td{Brain trit sum mod 3}\td{0 (conserved)}}
\tr{\td{Rauzy tiles}\td{a: 136, b: 74, c: 40}}
\tr{\td{a/b ratio}\td{1.84 (converges to plastic number ρ ≈ 1.325)}}
}

\p{The trit distribution is heavily 0-dominant because the frontocentral electrodes show theta-dominant (not alpha or beta) activity at these impedances. With better contact, expect more -1/+1 variance. The 5 alpha-dominant heleks and 2 beta-dominant heleks are genuine state transitions.}
}

\subtree{\title{Aptos Commit-Reveal Protocol}
\taxon{design}

\p{Each helek produces a \code{commit_hash} (first 16 hex chars of SHA-256 of spectral summary). The commit-reveal scheme for on-chain randomness:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Commit} (before helek elapses): post \code{commit_hash} on Aptos. This is a binding commitment to the next brain state.}
\li{\strong{Reveal} (after helek elapses): post the full spectral summary (5 band powers + 4 channel trits). Anyone can verify SHA-256 matches the committed hash.}
\li{\strong{Seed derivation}: first 8 bytes of SHA-256 → uint64 SplitMix64 seed. Deterministic color and tiling position follow.}
}

\p{This is \strong{proof of brain} — a randomness beacon that requires a human neural system in the loop. Unlike drand (BLS threshold signatures at 30s rounds), this provides:}
\ul{
\li{500 Hz source rate (vs drand's 0.033 Hz)}
\li{Biometric uniqueness (each brain produces different entropy)}
\li{Physiological attestation (trit correlates with cognitive state)}
\li{Unpredictable even to the subject (you cannot predict your own alpha rhythm)}
}
}

\subtree{\title{Rauzy Tiling as Generative Index}
\taxon{definition}

\p{The Rauzy substitution (a→ab, b→ac, c→a) is natively GF(3). Each helek maps to a tile in the Rauzy fractal. The tiling grows as new heleks are recorded — each session extends the fractal. The plastic number ρ ≈ 1.3247 governs the growth rate.}

\p{For asteroid indexing: each newly discovered asteroid receives the next Rauzy tile position and a brain-color from the EEG entropy at discovery time. The fractal is the registry — zoom in and the same three-tile self-similar structure appears at every scale.}
}

